Good morning everyone. I am going to explain smth for people to understand
I've received lots of DMs recently asking me how same agent code can have different results
before you ask me this, please take some time to understand what the agent code actually is doing
lots of people are forking top agents code and making changes without understanding what the agent does
lots of agents are providing tools to the LLM to use
the LLM sometimes might pick tool A but then next time maybe it'll choose tool B
so you will not always see the same result
if you'd like it to be the same result every time, then you'll have to change the agent structure

Even though it’s the exact same miner code and exact same validator code, there are so many variables in the random statistical soup of LLM inference that the responses can be slightly different. Exponentiate this over the hundreds of inference calls being done per sandbox run, each referencing the last, and you get agents which are calling entirely different sets of tools

Consider 95% determinism—for a given input, let's assume the output is 95% likely to be the same (this is way higher than what it actually is, even for the same seed). Then after two calls, where the second is based on the first, the chances of the same response are 95% * 95% = 90.25%. Now take 30 calls: 95%^30 = 21.46%. 100 calls: 95%^100 = 0.59%. There is *half a percent* chance that two validators will get the same response on a single evaluation run. Over 50 evaluation runs? These minor differences compound very quickly.

Even if two agents are running the exact same code, the results don’t always match up. That’s because LLMs work kind of like people—our thoughts aren’t 100% repeatable. You might ask someone the same question twice and get slightly different wording or reasoning, depending on mood, timing, or what detail caught their attention first.
ow scale that up. Imagine every tiny difference stacking on top of the last one across dozens or hundreds of steps. At first, maybe 95% of the time you’d expect the same answer. But after two steps, that drops to ~90%. After 30 steps, you’re already down to about 20%. After 100 steps, it’s basically a coin flip whether the chain of thought matches at all. And if you run the whole process 50 times, the odds of two runs being identical are practically zero.
It’s like having two people take the same test. Even if they studied the exact same way, once you factor in small things—like how they interpret a tricky question or recall a fact—their answers won’t be identical. Multiply that by hundreds of questions, and the differences snowball.
